> <sup>402</sup> My reading of this very obscure passage–*jināmhase
> rūpinin Lacchin* or *rūpinī Lacchī*–is suggested by my husband, and
> differs from that of Dr. Neumann, who has felt compelled to doctor the
> text. Commentary: 'Defeated by the goddess Sirī (Śrī) clad in human
> dress'–*i.e.*, Isidāsī, as personating the fickle goddess of chance.
> Thus they call her 'Luck!' I cannot believe that, had the young
> *divorcee* been *enceinte*, she would have been sent home so
> ignominiously, or that the tale would have been silent about the child
> when born.

